http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: List the influence of personal values on health practices.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify and write a list of personal health-related values (e.g., visiting the dentist every 6 months, waiting for marriage to be sexually active, etc.) and explain how they influence personal health choices.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify how some health choices influence unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify health risk behaviors of adolescents using tobacco and the potential for increased frequency of use and/or addiction.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe how school policies can influence health promotion.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe the changes in the lunch menu and vending machines as a result of implementing the School Wellness Policy.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe how family values and behaviors influence the health of adolescents.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe ways in which families communicate and model behaviors which can influence the health behaviors of adolescents.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Discuss the influence of culture on health behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify how culture conveys accurate and inaccurate messages about appearance and body image.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe how peers influence unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe the different ways peers can positively or negatively influence another's self-image / self-esteem (e.g., criticizing appearance, not accepting of differences, bullying, shunning, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify how the school can affect personal health practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe how school counselors, nurses and administrators help students report or obtain assistance when faced with unsafe situations.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how information from the media influences health behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe how the media sends mixed messages about nutrition (e.g., indulging in foods vs. thin is in).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Interpret the influence of technology on personal health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Interpret how new forms of technology can help people monitor individual health (e.g., blood-glucose monitors, home cholesterol tests, blood pressure kits, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Indicate how the perceptions of norms influence healthy and unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recognize that perceptions of norms can negatively or positively influence behaviors (e.g., most are not sexually active, not all students smoke, not everyone is dating).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the influence of personal beliefs on health practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify how an individual's personal beliefs are expressed through personal health decisions.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Discuss how some risky choices can influence the likelihood of unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss how using tobacco can increase the risk of using marijuana and other gateway drugs.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify how public health policies can influence disease prevention.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Cite examples of public health policies and how they help keep communities healthy (e.g., policies on water and air quality, tobacco related policies, immunization policies for school –aged children, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how the family influences the health of adolescents.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Interpret family influences on health through guidelines given to the adolescent regarding social activities (e.g., dating, teen parties, tobacco use, peer pressure, sexuality, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the influence of culture on health beliefs, practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Give examples of family members' roles and family structures in different cultures (e.g., determined by age, education, employment, order of respect, etc.) which influence health beliefs, practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe how peers influence healthy and unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe the different ways peers can respond in a bullying situation.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze how the school and community can affect personal health practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine ways that the school and community encourage students to use appropriate skills to avoid, resolve and cope with conflict.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze how messages from the media influence health behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Analyze the approaches used to convey messages through media to influence eating behaviors and food selections.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the influence of technology on personal and family health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine how new types of technological equipment, used for diagnosing health/medical conditions, can contribute to the early detection of diseases and enhance medical treatment.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain how the perceptions of norms influence healthy and unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Give examples of adolescent perceived norms which can result in healthy and/or unhealthy behaviors (e.g., teenagers submitting to sex because they think it is expected; teenagers are risk takers, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain the influence of personal values and beliefs on individual health practice and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain how personal values and beliefs can encourage abstinence from risk behaviors (e.g., bullying, sexual activity, using tobacco, alcohol, or other drugs, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe how some health risk behaviors can influence the likelihood of engaging in unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe how using alcohol can lead to poor decision-making (e.g., fighting, sexual activity, using other drugs, driving).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain how school and public health policies can influence health promotion and disease prevention.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify the healthier food choices that students make as a result of implementing the School Wellness Policy.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how the family impacts the health of individuals.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Distinguish the type of communication that occurs between parents and adolescents regarding abstinence and the resources that parents can provide to adolescents regarding health decisions and abstinence.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how society supports and challenges health beliefs, practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe how societal or cultural beliefs influence health and medical practices (e.g., vegetarian diets, alternative medicine, acupuncture, medicine pouch, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how adolescents influence healthy and unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine how peers can positively or negatively influence others regarding the use of anti-social words and actions.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Assess how the school and community can influence health practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Assess programs ("Prom Promise", "Don't Drink and Drive," "White Lies," etc.) that can help students identify, avoid or cope with potentially dangerous situations.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the effect of media on personal health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Compare and contrast how media can send messages about behaviors that can have a positive or negative effect on personal health and wellness.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the impact of technology on personal and family health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine how technology can have adverse effects on personal and family health (e.g., Internet pornography, chat lines, inaccurate health information).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how norms influence health-related behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recognize how perceived norms may not reflect actual health behaviors (e.g., teen alcohol use, tobacco use, sexual activity, dating, regular physical activity, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine the influence of personal values on health practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discover how personal values guide health practices and behaviors related to eating, exercising, personal hygiene, relationships, seeking medical care, etc.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how some health risk behaviors can influence the likelihood of taking part in other unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Debate how using tobacco can increase the risk of using marijuana and/or describe how using alcohol can lead to poor decision making.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how public health policies and government regulations can influence health promotion and disease prevention.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine how public health policies and government regulations can impact the accessibility of health care.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze how the family influences the health of individuals.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recognize the differences in health practices and behaviors (e.g., medical care, hygiene practices, safety behaviors, etc.) of families from different countries / cultures and how this influences the health of each family member.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze how culture supports and challenges health beliefs, practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Compare and contrast how cultural health beliefs, practices and behaviors can impact health and longevity.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze how peers influence healthy and unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Analyze how peers can influence how an individual is perceived and/or accepted into a social group.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate how the school and community can impact personal health practice and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Evaluate programs that impact and empower students to develop counter marketing campaigns directed towards improving health behaviors and reducing risk of injury.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate the effect of media on personal and family health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Compare and contrast how food commercials have a positive or negative impact on personal and family health decisions.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate the impact of technology on personal, family and community health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Appraise the impact of the lack of advanced technology on the health of individuals in developing countries.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze how the perceptions of norms influence healthy and unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine perceived norms of adolescent behavior and how personal values and beliefs can influence actual individual health practices and behaviors related to promoting a tobacco-free, alcohol-free and other drug-free lifestyle.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the influence of personal values and beliefs on individual health practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine health behavior data that is self-reported vs. actual (e.g., date rape, sexual abuse, physical abuse, shaken baby syndrome, suicide attempts, alcohol and drug use) and the influence personal values and beliefs have on individual health practices and behaviors.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze how some health risk behaviors can influence the likelihood of engaging in unhealthy behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Make inferences on how selected health risk behaviors can be associated with other unhealthy actions (e.g., using drugs and fighting, being sexually active, drinking and driving, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze how public health policies and government regulations can influence health promotion and disease prevention.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Review and interpret the International Health Regulations and the impact of AIDS, Avian Influenza and Pandemic Flu transmission to developing countries.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Students will demonstrate the ability to access valid information and products and services to enhance health.
Name a person who can help promote health and wellness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify parents, teachers, or doctors as people who can teach others about good health.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Name ways to locate a school helper for a health-related situation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe how to find an adult at school who could help when another student has a bloody nose and/or name the school office as a place to find a school health helper (e.g., principal, school nurse, school counselor, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose a professional who can help promote health and wellness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Indicate an individual who could answer questions about dental health (e.g., dentist, dental hygienist, school nurse etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: List ways to locate a community helper for a health-related situation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate the ability to call 911 in an emergency.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify trusted adults and professionals who can help promote health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine who to go to when you feel ill or have an injury on the playground (e.g., principal, school nurse, teacher, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify ways to locate school and community health helpers.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate how to find a sign in a store window that indicates it is a safe place for children, and/or explain the actions to take to seek assistance from the school nurse.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: State characteristics of valid health products and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: State that valid health services are provided by trusted individuals such as doctors, nurses, counselors, etc., who may work in hospitals, clinics, health departments, or other facilities.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Name resources from home and school that provide valid health information.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Name a resource person at school (e.g., school nurse, food service coordinator, counselor, media/technology specialist, etc.) that can help provide or find valid health information.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize characteristics of valid health information and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify Internet sources that end in .gov or .org as sources that usually provide valid health information.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify characteristics of valid health information, products and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: State that one characteristic of valid health products is that products are approved by trusted sources such as the Food & Drug Administration and the Consumer Product Safety Commission.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Locate resources from home, school and community that provide valid health information.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Use the Internet to locate information about tobacco-use prevention from voluntary or governmental health organizations.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Indicate the validity of health products.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Indicate the validity of health products by seeking recommendations from health professionals (e.g., pharmacist, dietician, physician) and the product's price, ingredients, benefits, and warranty information.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Find valid health information from home.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Find a government health agency on the Internet or in a telephone directory that could be used to find out more information about HIV/AIDS.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: List the accessibility of health-related products.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: List where a user/consumer could find, borrow or purchase protective gear to use during wheeled sport activities (e.g., bicycling, roller-blading, skateboarding, using mopeds, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize circumstances that may require professional health services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recognize that if someone is not breathing, emergency assistance is needed (e.g., have another person call 9-1-1) and provide rescue breathing if trained.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Find valid and reliable health services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Find services provided by voluntary health organizations such as the American Red Cross, American Heart Association, American Lung Association, American Cancer Society, etc.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain the validity of health information.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain how health information from Internet sources that end in .gov or .org can be more reliable sources of information.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Locate valid health information from school and community.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Locate valid mental health information from school (e.g., school psychologist) and community sources (e.g., hospital, mental health crisis center, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify how to access products that enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify how to access products for acne that have been approved by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine situations that require health services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine at an accident site who needs immediate professional health services (e.g., an individual with no heart beat, "cardiac arrest," or head injuries, or a fracture needs help before someone who is vomiting, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Select valid and reliable health products.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Select valid and reliable personal health products that are provided to pre-adolescents and adolescents (e.g., skin medications, soaps, lotions, dental care products, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the validity of health information, products and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Analyze the quality of weight loss programs by determining whether the programs promote gradual weight loss, have qualified staff, and promote healthy eating and/or physical activity.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Access valid health information from home, school and community.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Access valid information related to the cause and prevention of injuries by using the Internet. (e.g., National Center for Injury Prevention and Control, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine the accessibility of products that enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine vitamin and mineral supplements that have been approved by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe situations that may require professional health services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe emergency illnesses (e.g., cardiac arrest, stroke, diabetic coma, severe asthma attack, etc.) and injuries (e.g., third degree burns) that require professional health care services.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Locate valid and reliable health products and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate the ability to locate valid community mental health services (e.g., crisis center, counselor, psychologist, psychiatrist, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Assess how to determine the validity of health information, products and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Assess the validity of teeth whitening products and whether the products are government approved, studied or researched and/or assess teeth whitening services by determining whether they are provided by qualified professionals (e.g., dentists, orthodontists, physicians, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Utilize resources from school and community that provide valid health information.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Search the Internet and select community organizations (e.g., police department, sheriff's department, National Crime Prevention Council) that provide valid health information regarding crime prevention.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Investigate the accessibility of products and services that enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Investigate the accessibility of school and community programs, spaces and facilities for physical activity (e.g., gymnasiums, tracks, trails, paths, baseball/softball/soccer fields, youth organizations, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine when professional health services may be required.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify when eating habits and/or weight loss techniques may not be having a positive effect on the body and that professional health services are recommended.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Select valid and reliable health products and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Select a health service when seeking help for self or others when there may be a risk of a suicide attempt.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate the validity of health information, products and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Evaluate alcohol and other drug information (e.g., instructions, accuracy, guidelines regarding the reliability of the source, if the information is up-to-date, etc.) and/or research a product to determine its reliability, effectiveness and safety.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Use resources from home, school and community that provide valid health information.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Read a medicine label to determine the correct dosage to administer based on a person's age and/or weight, side effects and contraindications.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine the accessibility of products and services that enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine the accessibility of HIV/AIDS and STI testing sites for youth.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine when professional health services may be required.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine when a friend has problems with unhealthy eating behaviors and help him/her to seek professional health services.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Access valid and reliable health products and services.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Access valid and reliable health products and services in the community or on the Internet (e.g., healthy diets, weight management, nutritional supplements, nutritionist, medical specialist, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Students will demonstrate the ability to use interpersonal communication skills to enhance health and avoid or reduce health risks.
Identify healthy ways to express needs.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Indicate appropriate ways to express needs in a variety of situations (e.g., disagreeing with a friend, asking for help with buckling a safety belt, going to the restroom, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: State listening skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Brainstorm a list of listening skills appropriate in a variety of classroom and home situations (e.g., when a teacher speaks, during sharing time, when a parent is speaking, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: State ways to respond when in an unwanted situation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Name assertive responses or skills that could be used in an unwanted situation at school (e.g., saying No; walking away, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: State ways to tell a trusted adult if feeling threatened.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Show how to tell an adult about a student that is pushing and shoving in the hall, on the playground, or at the bus stop.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe healthy ways to express needs, wants and feelings.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Show appropriate ways to express feelings when upset (e.g., tone and volume of voice, waiting ones turn, not hitting, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify listening skills related to health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Show the listening skills a good listener uses when someone else is talking (e.g., not interrupting, not talking, paying attention, making eye contact, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify ways to respond when in a threatening or dangerous situation

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe appropriate ways to respond when separated from your family at an event (e.g., fair, shopping, school or community event, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify ways to tell a trusted adult if threatened or harmed by another person.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss how to tell an adult that you are being bullied.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate healthy ways to express needs, wants and feelings.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe how to appropriately express a strong feeling like anger (e.g., I messages, being calm, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate listening skills to enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate listening skills that promote better relationships (e.g., not interrupting, paying attention, not talking to others, explaining how to be kind).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate ways to respond when in an unwanted, threatening or dangerous situation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Illustrate different ways to respond when there is someone knocking on the door when home alone or parent is asleep.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate ways to tell a trusted adult if threatened or harmed.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate ways a student can communicate with a trusted adult after being offered a ride home by someone they do not feel comfortable with or they do not know.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Name effective nonverbal communication skills to enhance health and wellness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: List nonverbal interpersonal communication skills that build healthy friendships (e.g., eye contact, tone of voice, body language, and facial expressions).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify refusal strategies that reduce health risks.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Tell how to politely refuse a snack or second helping when feeling full.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Suggest nonviolent strategies to manage conflict.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify possible choices to consider when being teased about physical appearance.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Illustrate how to ask for assistance with a difficult personal situation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Role play how to ask for help when bullied by a friend, threatened by someone unknown, and/or when basic needs are not met.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain effective verbal communication skills to enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss how to express feelings in a healthy way (e.g., I messages, respect, tact, empathy, etc.) with a variety of situations (e.g., experiencing the death of a pet, seriously ill family member, school lunch spills on clothing, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Show refusal skills that avoid health risks.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Tell in your own words how to refuse when offered a tobacco product.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Practice nonviolent strategies to resolve conflict.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate nonviolent strategies to resolve a conflict when there is a misunderstanding between friends (e.g., how to stay calm and not make the conflict worse; listen to the other person; identify choices or resolve conflict; compromise on a choice that is fair for those involved, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Model how to ask for support to enhance personal health and wellness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice asking for support when trying to control anger, change a habit or improve listening skills.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate effective verbal and nonverbal communication skills to enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Model effective expression of feelings using verbal and nonverbal communication skills (e.g., empathy, grief, sadness, a friend's relative passes away, cultural/ethnic differences of showing respect, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate refusal skills that avoid or reduce health risks.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Model how to refuse a food because it is less healthy or because of personal preference.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate nonviolent strategies to manage or resolve conflict.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Present a compromise situation that is fair for both persons when two classmates want to use the same piece of classroom equipment or classmates disagree about a game rule interpretation during recess.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate how to ask for assistance to enhance personal health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice how to ask for assistance when a friend is being bullied or teased or a friend may have a dangerous object at school such as a gun, knife or other weapon.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Investigate effective communication skills to enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Select movies, magazines, books, or other media to identify interpretations of verbal and non-verbal communication skills that are promoting positive relationships.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose refusal skills to avoid or reduce health risks.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Present how to say no, give a reason or excuse, suggest another activity, use humor, change the subject, delay, say no again, and walk away, to refuse the pressure to use alcohol.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose effective conflict management strategies.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice how to make an apology as well as to accept an apology for having made a hurtful comment.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose how to ask for assistance to enhance the health of self.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Model how to ask for assistance (e.g., sadness due to terminal illness of family member or close friend, partner not working on a project, sibling conflict) to enhance health.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate effective communication skills to enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Using verbal communication skills perform what to do in an unsafe situation, such as bullying, harassment, etc. that will show care and concern (e.g., say no, walk away, contact a trusted adult, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Model refusal and negotiation skills to avoid or reduce health risks.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform a skit depicting teens negotiating when jealousy or hurt pride are an issue (e.g., take time before meeting other person, allow each person to express themselves uninterrupted, ask questions of each other, keep brainstorming until a good solution is reached for both persons).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Model effective conflict resolution strategies.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Show conflict resolution skills (e.g., how to stay calm, listen, try to see the opposing point of view, offer a way out, apologize or accept an apology, work together to identify choices to resolve the conflict, seek the assistance of a mediator, compromise on a choice that is fair to all persons, etc.) used in a situation in which peers are not getting along.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Model how to ask for assistance to enhance the health of others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate how to ask for assistance when feeling overwhelmed by feelings (e.g., depression, sadness, anger, rejection, grief, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Apply effective verbal and non-verbal communication skills to enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Prepare a conversation, which includes both verbal and non-verbal communication skills, between friends when not wanting to cheat on homework.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate refusal and negotiation skills to avoid or reduce health risks.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate refusal and negotiation skills that may be used when someone brings alcohol to a student gathering.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate effective conflict management or resolution strategies.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice conflict management or resolution strategies when a student is concerned about a rumor or a hurtful comment made (e.g., how to stay calm, assess risk of violence, seek the assistance of mediator, offer a way out, identify choices to resolve the conflict, compromise on a choice that is fair to all persons, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate how to ask for assistance to enhance the health of self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate how a teen can ask for help when faced with a stressful situation (e.g., overwhelmed at home, school, suicide, relationships).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Model skills for communicating effectively with others to enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform a conversation using effective communication skills (e.g., I messages, verbal/nonverbal communication and feedback, attentive listening, assertive communication, etc.) when family life/conflicts or class expectations become overwhelming.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Apply refusal, negotiation and collaboration skills to enhance health and avoid or reduce health risks.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Illustrate a situation where friends pressured to consume alcohol use refusal or negotiation skills (e.g., saying no, suggesting another activity, leaving the situation safely, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Apply strategies to manage or resolve interpersonal conflicts without harming self or others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice negotiation or collaboration strategies to use when a peer is under the influence of alcohol or other drugs and places self at risk.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Illustrate how to offer assistance to enhance the health of self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Model ways a person would offer assistance to a person who has experienced grief, stress/distress, or date rape, etc.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Use skills for communicating effectively with family, peers and others to enhance health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Develop a conversation (e.g., I messages, verbal/nonverbal communication and feedback, attentive listening, assertive communication, etc.) between friends demonstrating an understanding of effective grief process skills.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate refusal, negotiation and collaboration skills to enhance health and avoid or reduce health risks.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Reconstruct a scenario between friends (e.g., one friend offers the other a chance to try a ―new drug‖) where a conflict is resolved by using refusal and/or negotiation skills and a conversation using effective communication techniques.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate strategies to prevent, manage or resolve interpersonal conflicts without harming self or others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate how to use humor, apologize or accept an apology, collaborate to identify choices, seek the help of a lay or professional counselor, compromise on a choice that is fair to all involved (e.g., boyfriend/girlfriend relationship, friends, classmates, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate how to ask for and offer assistance to enhance the health of self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate how a friend can seek professional assistance for a health-related situation (e.g., eating disorder, pregnancy, suicide, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Students will demonstrate the ability to use decision-making skills to enhance health.
Identify health-related situations.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: List ways to stay safe while traveling to and from school, and/or select an example of an ―always‖ and a ―sometimes‖ after school snack.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify when assistance is needed for health-related situations.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain that medicine should only be given to children by parents or trusted adults, and/or identify a dangerous situation that requires help (e.g., someone is hurt or being hurt, when you have an ―uh-oh‖ feeling inside, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain safe behaviors when walking, playing, and riding in a vehicle or describe the difference between an ―always‖ and a ―sometimes‖ after school snack.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe situations when assistance is needed for a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine when adult help is needed to take medicine (e.g., asthma attack, allergy reaction, headache, etc.), or describe a dangerous situation that requires adult assistance (e.g., someone is being hurt by an adult [abuse], when the actions of another person gives you an ―uh-oh‖ feeling inside, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify situations when a health-related decision is needed.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify how the food guide pyramid can be used to guide the choice of an after school snack and/or discuss safe walking practices in challenging situations (e.g., walking alone, crossing streets, no sidewalk, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Differentiate between situations when a health-related decision can be made individually or when assistance is needed.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Suggest rules for safe use of medicines (e.g., only take medicine under the guidance of an adult, only take medicine prescribed for you, always take the proper dosage, etc.) and/or differentiate between dangerous situations requiring adult assistance and those that do not (e.g., taking a ride from someone you know without parental permission).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Indicate routine health-related situations.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Indicate personal choices that contribute to personal health and wellness (e.g., brushing teeth, getting plenty of rest/sleep, washing hands, etc.) and/or demonstrate everyday decisions that contribute to being a good friend (e.g., be a good listener, help a friend when needed, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify when support is needed when making a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss how adults can help an individual avoid drugs and stay safe (e.g., don't smoke in the car).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Tell options to health-related issues or problems.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: State ways to get friends to be physically active during recess.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Indicate the possible consequences of each choice when making a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify the safety-related pros and cons of using different forms of transportation to and from school (e.g., bus, car, walking, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify a healthy choice when making a decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify a healthy after school snack.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain situations that may require a thoughtful health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain what to do when approached with an uncomfortable request or situation.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine when help is needed to make a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Give examples of situations involving tobacco use that may require the help of an adult (e.g., rode in the car with a sibling and they were smoking, continued pressure from a friend to smoke, peer pressure to steal a parent's tobacco, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Indicate healthy alternatives to health-related issues or problems.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Tell ways to exercise safely in a variety of weather conditions (e.g., cold, wet, snowy, hot and humid, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the possible consequences of each option when making a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe the potential outcomes of strategies for practicing swimming safety (e.g., swimming with a buddy, diving only where permitted, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine a healthy alternative when making a decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine a healthy option from a list of school party foods.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify health-related situations that may require a thoughtful decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify what to do to stay safe when someone comes to the house and you are home alone (e.g., not answer the door, call an adult, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze when assistance is needed in making a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine what to do when a friend has requested a secret be kept and you are uncertain if it is a good idea to keep the secret (e.g., friend tried smoking, abuse by a relative, friend vomiting after eating, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: List healthy options to health-related issues or problems.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: List suggestions for life-long physical activities (e.g., soccer, swimming, bicycling, softball, aerobics, golf, frisbee golf, etc.) that promote wellness.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Predict the potential outcomes of each option when making a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Predict the possible consequences of various safety practices when riding a bike (e.g., wearing a helmet, using hand signals, riding on the correct side of the road, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose a healthy option when making a decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Make a healthier selection when eating at a fast food restaurant.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the outcomes of a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain the consequences of using positive peer pressure to avoid using drugs.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Name conditions that can help or hinder healthy decision making.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: List how wearing safety equipment when skateboarding or 4-wheeling can assist with making a health-enhancing decision.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain when health-related situations require a thoughtful decision-making process.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Differentiate between what to do when someone is teased and when someone is bullied.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain when individual or adult supported decision making is appropriate.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain how family meal plans/eating practices include individual and family decisions.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify healthy and unhealthy options to health-related issues or problems.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe various options for dealing with an offer by a best friend to try cigarettes.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the potential short-term impact of each choice on self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss the impact of not following family rules on the individual and his/her family.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Distinguish healthy options over unhealthy options when making a decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Distinguish between foods that are nutrient dense and foods that are low in nutrients when selecting a snack.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Predict the results of a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain the potential results of choosing to be drug free.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe situations that can help or hinder healthy decision-making.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Outline ways in which peer pressure can influence decisions when boating and participating in other water-related activities with friends and/or family.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize when health-related situations require a thoughtful decision-making process.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine ways of dealing with being bullied.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine when independent or collaborative decision making is appropriate.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine nutrition decisions that a person can make independently and those that require input from others (e.g., vending machines – what to purchase from the machine, what to make available in the machine).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Differentiate between healthy and unhealthy choices to health-related issues or problems.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Differentiate between unhealthy and healthy ways to manage weight and select healthy approaches to weight loss.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine the potential short-term impact of each option on self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine how abstaining from sexual activity has a positive impact on the individuals involved, the relationship, and the boy/girlfriend.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose healthy choices over unhealthy choices when making a decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Illustrate different strategies for removing oneself from an environment where peers are smoking (e.g., party, city park, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine the consequences of a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine the potential outcomes of going to a party where friends are likely using drugs.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify circumstances that can help or hinder healthy decision making.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain how parents setting curfews or chaperones at a dance can assist teens in making health-enhancing decisions.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine when health-related situations require the application of a thoughtful decision-making process.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine the best actions to take to assist a friend when they communicate that they are being bullied.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Distinguish when individual or collaborative decision making is appropriate.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Debate the school food policy (e.g., how much control should the school have over what food is served at a school dance).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Distinguish between healthy and unhealthy alternatives to health-related issues or problems.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Analyze the different options for addressing a friend who has recently started smoking.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Predict the potential short-term impact of each alternative on self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Present convincing reasons to abstain from sexual behaviors by examining the negative consequences on self, boy/girlfriend and family.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose healthy alternatives over unhealthy alternatives when making a decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Choose a balanced/nutritious meal when selecting breakfast and/or lunch items at school.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the outcomes of a health-related decision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine the potential outcomes of different ways of supporting a friend in being alcohol-, tobacco- and drug-free.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine barriers to healthy decision making.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine personal barriers to practicing sun safety (e.g., wearing sunscreen, avoiding tanning beds, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Outline the value of applying a thoughtful decision-making process to a health-related situation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Consider the benefit of using a thoughtful decision-making process in making a choice related to situations involving tobacco and/or alcohol.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Assess when independent or collaborative decision making is appropriate.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Assess the role of a parent being involved in making a decision about an unplanned teen pregnancy.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Propose alternative choices to health-related issues or problems.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Specify the choices for a person who suspects he/she has a sexually transmitted infection (STI).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the potential short and long-term outcome of each alternative on self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Analyze the short and long-term health effects of marijuana use.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine the health-enhancing choice when making decisions.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Determine the proper action to help a friend, who is considering becoming sexually active, make the health-enhancing choice of abstinence.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Assess the potential success or consequence of health-related decisions.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Assess the decision of how to help a friend who has an eating disorder.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine barriers that can hinder healthy decision making.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine personal barriers to getting annual checkups (e.g., cost, family values, cultural beliefs, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Determine the value of applying a thoughtful decision-making process in health-related situations.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Consider the benefit of soliciting community feedback on local tobacco initiatives.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Justify when individual or collaborative decision making is appropriate.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Defend which individual is responsible for providing protection when a married couple does not want to become pregnant.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Generate alternatives to health-related issues or problems.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Generate healthy options for a teen that is pregnant and/or a teen that is fathering a child.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Predict the potential short and long-term impact of each alternative on self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Predict the short and long-term impact of driving under the influence of alcohol on self and others (e.g., passengers, other drivers, parents, pedestrians, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Defend the healthy choice when making decisions.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Defend the choice of telling a trusted adult about a friend in an abusive relationship.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate the effectiveness of health-related decisions.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Select various strategies for reducing stress and assess the potential success of these strategies.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Students will demonstrate the ability to use goal-setting skills to enhance health.
Name personal health and wellness goals.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Name goals such as daily physical activity, getting adequate sleep, eating a balanced diet, and covering the mouth when coughing, etc.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Name who can help to achieve a personal health goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: State who can help when planning to be physically active after the school day (e.g., babysitter, parent, older sibling, relative, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Name actions to take toward achieving a short-term health goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: State a short-term goal to eat five or more fruits and vegetables every day and use a chart for one week to keep track of the fruit and vegetable intake.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify who can help to achieve a personal health goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify who can help in achieving a goal related to healthy eating (e.g., family member, teacher, babysitter, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify a short-term personal health goal and take action toward achieving the goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Suggest a short-term goal for maintaining or improving dental health (e.g., brushing, flossing, wearing a mouth guard, etc.) and chart the behavior.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify who can help when assistance is needed to achieve a personal health goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Suggest who can help when making a plan to deal with angry feelings in a healthy way (e.g., teacher, family member, babysitter, coach, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Select a personal health goal and track progress.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Select a personal health goal related to healthy sleep habits (e.g., bedtime routine, number of hours of sleep, morning routine, etc.) and track progress.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize resources to achieve a personal health goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recognize parents, teachers, or school counselor, etc., to help with a goal of managing angry feelings appropriately (e.g., taking deep breaths, listening to music, talking to a trusted adult, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Plan a personal health goal and how to monitor its progress.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Plan a personal health goal related to consuming more fruits and vegetables and use a chart for one week to track intake.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Discuss resources to help achieve a personal health goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss how trusted adults can assist a child in developing a school and home plan for taking medication.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Set a personal health goal and track progress toward its achievement.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Set a personal health goal related to personal hygiene and use a graph to track progress (e.g., deodorant use, washing with soap, hair care, dental practices, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify resources to assist in achieving a personal health goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Students identify trusted adults who can help them obtain a selected goal (e.g., set a goal, develop an action plan, establish a support system, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine personal health behaviors.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine current physical activity behaviors (e.g., type of physical activity, frequency of activity, intensity of activity, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify a goal to adopt a personal health practice.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify a goal to adopt a personal health practice for safety during wheeled sport activities (e.g., helmets, pads, proper clothing, appropriate speed, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop strategies to achieve a personal health goal.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Develop a plan to achieve a goal to drink at least eight glasses of water a day that includes the use of substitution of water for beverages that have little or no nutritional value and/or contain large amounts of caffeine. (e.g., develop a vision, set achievable short-term and long-term goals, develop an action plan, establish a support network, and set up a reward system, etc.)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain how personal health goals can vary with priorities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain how dietary goals might be modified due to a cultural or a religious holiday (e.g., fasting, holy day, etc.).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the effectiveness of personal health practices.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Analyze how current anger management practices are effective (e.g., how does one react when experiencing anger).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Select a goal to improve a personal health practice.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Reading for Literacy in Technical Subject

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students need to develop the skills that allow them to read complex informational health texts with independence and confidence. Students need to build an appreciation of the norms and conventions of reading in health, an understanding of domain-specific words and phrases, an attention to precise details, the capacity to evaluate detailed arguments, synthesize complex information and follow detailed descriptions and procedures. Students need to be able to gain knowledge from challenging texts that make use of elaborate diagrams and data to convey information and illustrate concepts.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Key Ideas and Details
Cite specific textual evidence to support analysis of health texts.
Determine the central ideas or conclusions of a text; provide an accurate summary of the text distinct from prior knowledge or opinions.
Follow precisely a multistep procedure when carrying out experiments or taking measurements.
Cite specific textual evidence to support analysis of health and wellness texts, attending to the precise details of explanations or descriptions.
Determine the central ideas or conclusions of a text; trace the text's explanation or depiction of a complex process, phenomenon, or concept; provide an accurate summary of the text.
Follow precisely a complex multistep procedure when carrying out experiments or taking measurements, attending to special cases or exceptions defined in the text.
Craft and Structure
Determine the meaning of symbols, key terms, and other domain-specific words and phrases as they are used in a specific health and wellness education context, relevant to grades 6-8 texts and topics.
Analyze the structure an author uses to organize a text, including how the major sections contribute to the whole and to an understanding of the topic.
Analyze the author's purpose in providing an explanation, describing a procedure, or discussing an experiment in a text.
Determine the meaning of symbols, key terms, and other domain-specific words and phrases as they are used in a specific scientific context relevant to grades 9-12 texts and topics.
Analyze the structure of the relationships among concepts in a text, including relationships among key terms (e.g., force, friction, reaction force, energy).
Analyze the author's purpose in providing an explanation, describing a procedure, or discussing an experiment in a text, defining the question the author seeks to address.
Integration of Knowledge and Ideas
Integrate quantitative information expressed in words in a text with a version of that information expressed visually (e.g., in a flowchart, diagram, model, graph, or table).
Distinguish among facts, reasoned judgment based on research findings and speculation in a text.
Compare and contrast the information gained from experiments, simulations, video or multimedia sources with that gained from reading a text on the same topic.

Translate quantitative information expressed in words in a text into visual form (e.g., a table or chart) and translate information expressed visually or mathematically (e.g., in an equation) into words.
Assess the extent to which the reasoning and evidence in a text support the author's claim or a recommendation for solving a scientific problem.
Compare and contrast findings presented in a text to those from other sources (including their own experiments), noting when the findings support or contradict previous explanations or accounts.
Range of Reading and Level of Text Complexity
By the end of grade 8 read and comprehend health texts in the grades 6-8 text complexity band independently and proficiently.
By the end of grade 12, read and comprehend health texts in the grades 9-12 text complexity band independently and proficiently.
Writing for Literacy in Technical Subjects

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students need to be able use writing as a key means to defend and assert claims, showing what they know about a subject and conveying what they have experienced, imagined, thought, and felt. They must be adept at gathering information, evaluating sources, and citing material accurately, reporting findings from their research and analysis of sources in a clear manner.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Text Types and Purposes
Write arguments to focus on discipline-specific content.
Introduce claim(s) about a topic or issue, acknowledge and distinguish the claim(s) from alternate or opposing claims, and organize the reasons and evidence logically.
Support claim(s) with logical reasoning and relevant, accurate data and evidence that demonstrate an understanding of the topic or text, using credible sources.
Use words, phrases, and clauses to create cohesion and clarify the relationships among claim(s), counterclaims, reasons, and evidence.
Establish and maintain a formal style.
Provide a concluding statement or section that follows from and supports the argument presented.
Write informative/explanatory texts, including scientific procedures/experiments or technical processes.

Introduce a topic clearly, previewing what is to follow; organize ideas, concepts and information into broader categories as appropriate to achieving purpose; include formatting (e.g., headings), graphics (e.g., charts, tables), and multimedia when useful to aiding comprehension.
Develop the topic with relevant, well-chosen facts, definitions, concrete details, quotations, or other information and examples.
Use appropriate and varied transitions to create cohesion and clarify the relationships among ideas and concepts.
Use precise language and domain-specific vocabulary to inform about or explain the topic.
Establish and maintain a formal style and objective tone.
Provide a concluding statement or section that follows from and supports the explanation or information presented.

Note: Students' narrative skills continue to grow in these grades. The Standards require that students be able to incorporate narrative elements effectively into arguments and informative/explanatory texts. In technical subjects, students must be able to write precise enough descriptions of the step-by-step procedures they use in their technical work that others can replicate them and (possibly) reach the same results.
Write arguments focused on discipline-specific content.

Introduce precise claim(s), distinguish the claim(s) from alternate or opposing claims, and create an organization that establishes clear relationships among the claim(s), counterclaims, reasons, and evidence.

Develop claim(s) and counterclaims fairly, supplying data and evidence for each while pointing out the strengths and limitations of both claim(s) and counterclaims in a discipline appropriate form and in a manner that anticipates the audience's knowledge level and concerns.

Use words, phrases, and clauses to link the major sections of the text, create cohesion, and clarify the relationships between claim(s) and reasons, between reasons and evidence, and between claim(s) and counterclaims.
Establish and maintain a formal style and objective tone while attending to the norms and conventions of the discipline in which they are writing.
Provide a concluding statement or section that follows from or supports the argument presented.
Write informative/explanatory texts, including scientific procedures/ experiments.

Introduce a topic and organize ideas, concepts, and information to make important connections and distinctions; include formatting (e.g., headings), graphics (e.g., figures, tables), and multimedia when useful to aiding comprehension.

Develop the topic with well-chosen, relevant, and sufficient facts, extended definitions, concrete details, quotations, or other information and examples appropriate to the audience's knowledge of the topic.
Use varied transitions and sentence structures to link the major sections of the text, create cohesion, and clarify the relationships among ideas and concepts.
Use precise language and domain-specific vocabulary to manage the complexity of the topic and convey a style appropriate to the discipline and context as well as to the expertise of likely readers.
